				<div id=3D"bodyContent" class=3D"vector-body ve-init-mw-desktopArticleT=
arget-targetContainer" aria-labelledby=3D"firstHeading" data-mw-ve-target-c=
ontainer=3D"">
					<div class=3D"vector-body-before-content">
							<div class=3D"mw-indicators">
		</div>

						<div id=3D"siteSub" class=3D"noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encycl=
opedia</div>
					</div>
					<div id=3D"contentSub"><div id=3D"mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Mea=
sure of a golfer's playing ability</div>
<p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golf" title=3D"Golf">golf</a>=
 <b>handicap</b> is a numerical measure of a golfer's ability, or potential=
 ability, that is used to enable players of different abilities to compete =
against one another. Better players are those with the lowest handicaps.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-TGcongu_2-=
0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(g=
olf)#cite_note-TGcongu-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-GDusga_3-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#cit=
e_note-GDusga-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Historically, rules relating to handicaps have varied from country t=
o country with many different systems in force around the world. Because of=
 incompatibilities and difficulties in translating between systems, the spo=
rt's governing bodies, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/USGA" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"USGA">USGA</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/The_R%26A" title=3D"The R&amp;A">The R&amp;A</a>, working wi=
th the various existing handicapping authorities, devised a new <b>World Ha=
ndicap System</b> (WHS) which began to be introduced globally in 2020.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-whs1_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#cite_note-whs1-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
whs2_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hand=
icap_(golf)#cite_note-whs2-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=20
</p>
<div class=3D"toclimit-3"><meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc"></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DHandicap_(golf)&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The earliest record of golf handicapping is thought to be from the late =
17th century, in a diary kept by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T=
homas_Kincaid" title=3D"Thomas Kincaid">Thomas Kincaid</a>, who was a stude=
nt in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edinburgh" title=3D"Edinburg=
h">Edinburgh</a>, Scotland, although the word <i>handicap</i> would not com=
e into use in golf until the late 19th century. The number of strokes to be=
 given and the holes on which they would be in effect was negotiated betwee=
n competing golfers prior to the start of play. According to <i>The Golfer'=
s Manual</i> by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Brougham_Far=
nie" title=3D"Henry Brougham Farnie">Henry Brougham Farnie</a>, examples of=
 agreed terms included "third-one" (one stroke every three holes), "half-on=
e" (one stroke every two holes), "one more" (a stroke a hole) and "two more=
" (two strokes a hole).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-usgahistory1_6-0" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#cite_note-us=
gahistory1-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#cite_note-7"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>During the late 19th century, taking the difference between the aver=
age of a golfer's best three scores during the year and <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Par_(golf)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Par (golf)=
">par</a> became the most widely used method of handicapping in England and=
 Scotland. As the sport grew, so did discontent with the fairness of handic=
apping, with less proficient players being particularly unhappy as it was m=
uch less likely for them to play to the standard of their three-score avera=
ge. Another issue was the lack of consideration in the system for the varyi=
ng difficulties of different courses which meant the handicap was not very =
portable.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-usgahistory2_8-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#cite_note-usgahistory2-8"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>
</p><p>In an attempt to remedy the problems with the basic handicap system =
and the many variations being used, the authorities in Great Britain and Ir=
eland sought to standardize. One of the first standard and equitable handic=
ap systems was introduced by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L=
adies_Golf_Union" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ladies Golf Union">Ladies =
Golf Union</a> (LGU) in the 1890s. This was largely achieved by means of un=
ion-assigned <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#Cours=
e_Rating">course ratings</a>, instead of clubs using their own. It was not =
until the formation of the British Golf Unions Joint Advisory Committee in =
1924 that the men's game fully coordinated to create an equitable handicap =
system, that included a uniform course rating, throughout Great Britain and=
 Ireland; the <i>Standard Scratch Score and Handicapping Scheme</i> was int=
roduced in 1926.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-conguhistory_9-0" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#cite_note-conguhist=
ory-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the United States, there was a single authority governing the spo=
rt, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/USGA" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"USGA">USGA</a>, which made moving to a single standard handicapp=
ing scheme somewhat easier. Introduced in 1911, the first national handicap=
 system was based on the British three-score average system. The biggest de=
velopment was a "par rating" system that assessed the average good score of=
 a scratch golfer on every course, which made the handicap more portable. I=
t also made clear that a player's handicap was intended to reflect their po=
tential rather than average play. Having initially allowed clubs to determi=
ne their own par ratings, the USGA quickly changed their minds and began as=
signing ratings. The USGA Handicap System has further developed through the=
 years, with an increase in the number of scores used for handicap calculat=
ions, the introduction of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equitabl=
e_Stroke_Control" title=3D"Equitable Stroke Control">Equitable Stroke Contr=
ol</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-usgahistory3_11-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#cite_note-usgahistory3-11=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> and improvements to the course rating system. However, the mo=
st significant change was the creation of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Slope_rating" title=3D"Slope rating">slope rating</a> system, w=
hich enabled handicaps to account for differences in difficulty between scr=
atch and bogey golfers. USGA Course and Slope Ratings now form the basis of=
 many other handicap systems.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-usgahistory4_12-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#cit=
e_note-usgahistory4-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>As the sport grew globally, associations around the world each creat=
ed or adapted their own rules relating to handicaps. By the early 21st cent=
ury, there were six major recognized handicapping systems in operation arou=
nd the world: USGA Handicap System, EGA Handicap System, CONGU Unified Hand=
icap System, Golf Australia Handicap System, South African Handicap System,=
 and Argentinian Handicap System. While these systems share some common fea=
tures, e.g. most use a common course rating system, they are not easily por=
table because their differences create difficulties in converting handicaps=
 between systems. In order to eliminate these problems the USGA and The R&a=
mp;A, working with the various existing handicapping authorities, devised a=
 new <i>World Handicap System</i> which was phased in globally in 2020.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-whs1_4-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#cite_note-whs1-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-whs2_5-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Han=
dicap_(golf)#cite_note-whs2-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Overview">Overview</h2><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DHandicap_(golf)&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Overview"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amateur_golf" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Amateur golf">Amateur golfers</a> who are members of golf clu=
bs are generally eligible for official handicaps on payment of the prevaili=
ng regional and national association annual fees. Official handicaps are ad=
ministered by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golf_club_(instituti=
on)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Golf club (institution)">golf clubs</a>=
 with the associations often providing additional peer reviewing for low ha=
ndicaps. Other systems, often free of charge, are available to golfers who =
are ineligible for official handicaps. Handicap systems are not generally u=
sed in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Professional_golf_tours" ti=
tle=3D"Professional golf tours">professional golf</a>. A golfer whose handi=
cap is zero is referred to as a <b>scratch golfer</b>, and one whose handic=
ap is approximately 18 as a <b>bogey golfer</b>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#c=
ite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>While the USGA administers its own handicapping system, the administ=
ration of handicapping systems in countries affiliated to The R&amp;A is th=
e responsibility of the national golf associations of those countries. Thes=
e bodies have different methods of producing handicaps but they are all gen=
erally based on calculating an individual player's playing ability from the=
ir recent history of rounds. Therefore, a handicap is not fixed but is regu=
larly adjusted to increases or decreases in a player's scoring. Some system=
s (e.g. World Handicap System, USGA, European Golf Association) involve cal=
culation of a playing handicap which is dependent on the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golf_course" title=3D"Golf course">course</a> being =
played and set of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Teeing_ground" t=
itle=3D"Teeing ground">tees</a> that are being used, whereas others (e.g. C=
ONGU's Unified Handicap System) just use the allocated handicap rounded to =
the nearest whole number.
</p><p>Contrary to popular opinion, a player's handicap is intended to refl=
ect a player's potential or "average best", not a player's overall average =
score. Statistically, low handicappers will play to their handicap more oft=
en because they are likely to be more consistent than higher handicappers.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Features_of_handicapping_sy=
stems">Features of handicapping systems</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection">=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/w/index.php?title=3DHandicap_(golf)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=
=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Features of handicapping systems"><span>edit</=
span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Scoring">Scoring</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DHandicap_(golf)&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Scoring"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The total number of strokes taken for a hole (or round) before accountin=
g for a golfer's handicap is called the <i>gross score</i> for that hole (o=
r round), and the number of strokes taken after subtracting any handicap al=
lowance is called the <i>net score</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-rule3_14-0" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#ci=
te_note-rule3-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =20
</p><p>Note that the <i>gross score</i> in 'world handicap system' is calcu=
lated as the number of strokes taken for a hole <b><i>+ the handicap allowa=
nce for that hole</i>.</b> The <i>adjusted gross score</i> in 'world handic=
ap system' is the <i>gross score</i> adjusted such that the maximum on any =
particular hole is the number of strokes taken for a hole + the handicap al=
lowance for that hole + 2 strokes (i.e. net double bogey). =20
</p><p>In handicap <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stroke_play" ti=
tle=3D"Stroke play">stroke play</a> competitions, a golfer's <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#Playing_or_course_handicap">play=
ing handicap</a> is subtracted from the total number of strokes taken to pr=
oduce a net score, which is then used to determine the final results. In ha=
ndicap <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stableford" title=3D"Stable=
ford">Stableford</a> competitions, a player's handicap is distributed accor=
ding to predetermined hole ratings (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Stroke_index" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Stroke index">stroke index</=
a>) and strokes deducted accordingly from each hole score before calculatin=
g the points for that hole. In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mat=
ch_play" title=3D"Match play">match play</a>, the handicap difference betwe=
en players (or teams) is used to determine the number of strokes the high h=
andicap player should receive from the low handicapper during the playing o=
f their round; each of these strokes are received on the lowest numbered st=
roke index holes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-rule3_14-1" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#cite_note-rule3-14"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> Stroke allowances may sometimes be reduced by a set percentage in o=
rder to maintain the level playing field; this is especially common in pair=
s and team competitions.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Course_Rating">Course Ratin=
g</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DHandicap_(=
golf)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Course Rati=
ng"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<p>Course Rating, (Standard) Scratch Score, Scratch Rating, and Standard Ra=
ting are largely equivalent ratings that are used to indicate the average "=
good score" by a scratch golfer for a set of tees on a golf course. For a p=
ar 72 course, the course rating is generally between 67 and 77. There are d=
ifferent methods of calculating the Course Rating, with the length of the c=
ourse and its obstacles being the biggest factors. Some systems use only th=
ese two, or even length alone, but most modern handicapping systems now use=
 the <i>USGA Course Rating</i> system which assesses the difficulty of all =
aspects of the course, e.g. altitude, wide or narrow <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Fairway_(golf)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fairway (=
golf)">fairways</a>, length of any rough, the size and contours of the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Green_(golf)" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Green (golf)">greens</a>, etc.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#cite_note-15=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Some handicapping systems provide for an adjustment to the course ra=
ting to account for variations in playing conditions on any given day, e.g.=
 course setup and weather, and it is against this adjusted rating that hand=
icaps are assessed and maintained. Examples of adjusted ratings are Playing=
 Conditions Calculation (World Handicap System), Competition Scratch Score =
(CONGU Unified Handicapping System), Daily Scratch Rating (Golf Australia H=
andicap System), and Calculated Rating (South African Handicap System).
</p><p>Analogous to course rating is the bogey rating, which is a measure o=
f the playing difficulty of a course for a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Bogey_golfer" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Bogey golfer">bogey g=
olfer</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Slope_Rating">Slope Rating<=
/h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DHandicap_(go=
lf)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Slope Rating"=
><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span=
></div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article=
: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slope_rating" title=3D"Slope rat=
ing">Slope rating</a></div>
<p>Devised by the USGA, the Slope Rating of a golf course describes the rel=
ative difficulty of a course for a bogey golfer compared to a scratch golfe=
r. Slope Ratings are in the range 55 to 155, with a course of standard rela=
tive difficulty having a rating of 113; the higher the number, the more rel=
atively difficult the course is.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Playing_or_course_handicap"=
>Playing or course handicap</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/i=
ndex.php?title=3DHandicap_(golf)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=
=3D"Edit section: Playing or course handicap"><span>edit</span></a><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In most major handicapping systems, a golfer does not use their exact ha=
ndicap (or handicap index) directly, but use it to produce their playing or=
 course handicap. For some systems, this means simply rounding the exact ha=
ndicap to the nearest whole number; however, systems that use slope ratings=
 require a more complex calculation to produce a course handicap with some =
also factoring in the course rating:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e {\mbox{Course handicap}}=3D{\frac {({\mbox{handicap index}}\times {\mbox{=
slope rating}})}{\mbox{113}}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mstyle displaystyle=3D"false" scriptlevel=3D"0">
            <mtext>Course handicap</mtext>
          </mstyle>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mrow>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mstyle displaystyle=3D"false" scriptlevel=3D"0">
                  <mtext>handicap index</mtext>
                </mstyle>
