-align: -1.838ex; width:76.156ex; height:5.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\=
mbox{Course handicap}}=3D{\frac {({\mbox{handicap index}}\times {\mbox{slop=
e rating}})}{\mbox{113}}}+({\mbox{course rating}}-{\mbox{par}})}"></span></=
dd></dl>
<p>The USGA and Golf Australia systems use the first calculation; the WHS, =
EGA, and Golf RSA systems use the second. Under CONGU's Unified Handicappin=
g System the exact handicap is rounded to the nearest whole number to produ=
ce the playing handicap, and in the Argentinian system the exact handicap i=
s used directly.
</p><p>A playing handicap may also refer to the stroke allowance for a give=
n competition dependent on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variati=
ons_of_golf" title=3D"Variations of golf">playing format</a>, and is genera=
lly calculated as a percentage of the course handicap.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Stroke_Index">Stroke Index<=
/h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DHandicap_(go=
lf)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Stroke Index"=
><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span=
></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stroke_Index" title=
=3D"Stroke Index">Stroke Index</a></div>
<p>The Stroke Index is a number that has been assigned to each hole on a go=
lf course, and usually printed on the scorecard, to indicate on which holes=
 handicap strokes should be applied. On an 18-hole course, each hole is ass=
igned a different number from 1 to 18 (1 to 9 on a 9-hole course). The lowe=
st numbers are usually given to the holes where a higher handicapper is mos=
t likely to benefit, and the highest numbers to the holes they are least li=
kely to benefit. Odd numbers will be allocated to either the first or secon=
d 9-holes (and even numbers to the other) to ensure a balanced distribution=
 of handicap strokes, and guidelines generally recommend avoiding having th=
e lowest numbers at the start or end of each nine in order to prevent early=
 stroke allowances in playoffs between golfers with similar handicaps or st=
rokes going unused if they are at the end.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#cite_no=
te-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Maximum_hole_score">Maximum=
 hole score</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Handicap_(golf)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: M=
aximum hole score"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equitable_Stroke_Con=
trol" title=3D"Equitable Stroke Control">Equitable Stroke Control</a></div>
<p>Most of the commonly used handicap systems seek to reduce the impact of =
very high scores on one or more individual holes on the calculation and upd=
ating of handicaps. This is achieved by setting a maximum score on each hol=
e, which is only used for handicapping purposes; i.e. it is not used for de=
termining results of competitions or matches. This <i>maximum hole score</i=
> is either a fixed number or a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ha=
ndicap_(golf)#Scoring">net score</a> relative to par. <i>Equitable Stroke C=
ontrol</i> (ESC) and <i>net double bogey</i> (also called Stableford Points=
 Adjustments) are the two most common mechanisms for defining a maximum hol=
e score.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Handicap_differential">Hand=
icap differential</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DHandicap_(golf)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: Handicap differential"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Handicap (or score) differentials are a feature of many handicapping sys=
tems. They are a standardized measure of a golfers performance, adjusted to=
 take account of the course being played. Normally the overall score will b=
e adjusted prior to the calculation, e.g. by means of <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#Maximum_hole_score">ESC or net double b=
ogey</a>. The course rating may also be adjusted to take account of conditi=
ons on the day.
</p><p>For handicapping systems that use course and slope ratings, a typica=
l calculation using the <i>score</i> (see above) is as follows:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e {\mbox{Handicap differential}}=3D{\frac {({\mbox{adjusted score}}-{\mbox{=
course rating}})\times {\mbox{113}}}{\mbox{slope rating}}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mstyle displaystyle=3D"false" scriptlevel=3D"0">
            <mtext>Handicap differential</mtext>
          </mstyle>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mrow>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mstyle displaystyle=3D"false" scriptlevel=3D"0">
                  <mtext>adjusted score</mtext>
                </mstyle>
              </mrow>
              <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mstyle displaystyle=3D"false" scriptlevel=3D"0">
                  <mtext>course rating</mtext>
                </mstyle>
              </mrow>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
              <mo>=C3=97<!-- =C3=97 --></mo>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mstyle displaystyle=3D"false" scriptlevel=3D"0">
                  <mtext>113</mtext>
                </mstyle>
              </mrow>
            </mrow>
            <mstyle displaystyle=3D"false" scriptlevel=3D"0">
              <mtext>slope rating</mtext>
            </mstyle>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\mbox{Handic=
ap differential}}=3D{\frac {({\mbox{adjusted score}}-{\mbox{course rating}}=
)\times {\mbox{113}}}{\mbox{slope rating}}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/5faed45aa95760b1a0055af0230ba8160834f471" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.338ex; width:63.36ex; height:6.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\m=
box{Handicap differential}}=3D{\frac {({\mbox{adjusted score}}-{\mbox{cours=
e rating}})\times {\mbox{113}}}{\mbox{slope rating}}}}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>The differentials are used both to calculate initial handicaps and maint=
ain existing ones, by taking a mean average of a set number of the best rec=
ent differentials (e.g. the USGA system uses the best 10 differentials from=
 the last 20 scores).
</p><p>For other handicapping systems, the differentials are simply the dif=
ference between the (adjusted) gross or net scores and a specified standard=
 rating (e.g. course rating, standard scratch score, etc.), and they are us=
ed in different ways to maintain handicaps.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Peer_review">Peer review</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DHandicap_(golf=
)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Peer review"><=
span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span><=
/div>
<p>In golf clubs, peer review is usually managed by an elected Handicap Sec=
retary who, supported by a small committee, conducts an Annual Review of th=
e handicaps of all members and assesses ad hoc requests from individual mem=
bers (usually when age or medium to long-term infirmity affects their playi=
ng ability). This gives uniformity to handicapping across their club for th=
e setting and maintenance of handicaps with the objective of establishing f=
air competition between golfers of all abilities.
</p><p>At the regional level, peer review is extended to include rigorous v=
alidation of the handicap returns of low handicap golfers. This ensures tha=
t only golfers of an appropriate standard gain entry to their elite tournam=
ents. Occasionally, golfers are excluded from the elite game as a consequen=
ce of being found to abuse the system. To a degree, these regional bodies a=
lso monitor the performance of and provide training for Handicap Secretarie=
s at the club level.
</p><p>Nationally, the peer review is extended further to assessing golfers=
 from external jurisdictions for their suitability for entry into their eli=
te international events. They also play a large part in periodic reviews of=
 the handicapping system itself to improve it for the future.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Handicapping_systems">Handi=
capping systems</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DHandicap_(golf)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit secti=
on: Handicapping systems"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"World_Handicap_System">Worl=
d Handicap System</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DHandicap_(golf)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: World Handicap System"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Due to the many different handicapping systems in use around the world, =
and the many inconsistencies within them, which makes it difficult to compe=
te on an equal footing where another handicap system is in use, the sports =
major governing bodies, in 2011 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Th=
e_R%26A" title=3D"The R&amp;A">The R&amp;A</a> and the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/USGA" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"USGA">USGA</a> be=
gan work on creation of a single uniform handicapping system to be used eve=
rywhere.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-whspr1119_18-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#cite_note-whspr1119-18"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> In February 2018, they announced that the World Handicap System (WHS=
) would be launched in 2020.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#cite_note-19"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> Once introduced, the World Handicap System will continue to be governe=
d by The R&amp;A and the USGA with the six existing major handicapping auth=
orities (the USGA, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Council_of_=
National_Golf_Unions" title=3D"Council of National Golf Unions">Council of =
National Golf Unions</a> (CONGU) in Great Britain and Ireland, the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/European_Golf_Association" title=3D"Europ=
ean Golf Association">European Golf Association</a> (EGA), <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golf_Australia" title=3D"Golf Australia">Golf Aust=
ralia</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSout=
h_African_Golf_Association&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1" class=3D"new"=
 title=3D"South African Golf Association (page does not exist)">South Afric=
an Golf Association</a> (SAGA), and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/w/index.php?title=3DArgentine_Golf_Association&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;redli=
nk=3D1" class=3D"new" title=3D"Argentine Golf Association (page does not ex=
ist)">Argentine Golf Association</a> (AAG)) administering the system at a l=
ocal level.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-whsqa2018_20-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#cite_note-whsqa2018-20"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-whspr1119_18-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#cite_note-whspr1119-18"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup>
</p><p>The WHS is based on the USGA Course and Slope Rating system, and lar=
gely follows the USGA Handicap System while also incorporating features fro=
m the six major existing handicap systems. For example, 8 differentials (li=
ke the Golf Australia system) are used after net double bogey adjustments (=
like the CONGU and EGA systems) for handicap calculations, and the WHS cour=
se/playing handicap includes a course rating adjustment (like the EGA syste=
m).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-whsqa2018_20-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#cite_note-whsqa2018-20"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> For players with current handicaps, their handicap records in the old sys=
tems will be used to produce WHS handicaps; the expectation is that most pl=
ayers will at most see a difference of one or two strokes, if any.
</p><p>A new WHS handicap requires several scores to be submitted; the reco=
mmendation is a minimum of 54 holes made up of any number of 9 or 18-hole r=
ounds in order to achieve a reasonable fair and accurate result, although h=
andicaps may be issued from a smaller sample. Handicap adjustments will be =
made upon submission of any 9 or 18-hole scores with updates published dail=
y; unlike some other systems both competitive and recreational rounds may b=
e submitted by all players (e.g. CONGU's Unified Handicapping System only a=
llows submission of non-qualifying scores by golfers in Category 2 or above=
). Ongoing handicaps are based on the average of the best 8 differentials, =
but with an "anchor" to prevent rapid increases that would not necessarily =
reflect the player's true potential. There is also a hole limit of "net dou=
ble bogey" for handicapping purposes in order to prevent one or two bad hol=
es from having a disproportionate effect.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-whspr1119_18-2=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(go=
lf)#cite_note-whspr1119-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"World_Handicap_System_overv=
iew">World Handicap System overview</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/w/index.php?title=3DHandicap_(golf)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14"=
 title=3D"Edit section: World Handicap System overview"><span>edit</span></=
a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A WHS handicap is calculated with a specific arithmetic formula that app=
roximates how many strokes above or below <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Par_(score)" title=3D"Par (score)">par</a> a player might be able t=
o play, based on the eight best scores of their last twenty rounds.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-whsmanual_21-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#cite_note-whsmanual-21"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>  The cal=
culation has several variables, including: the player's scores from their m=
ost recent rounds, the course rating, and the slope rating.
</p><p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#Handicap_=
differential">score differential</a> is calculated from each of the scores =
after any <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handicap_(golf)#Maximum_=
hole_score">net double bogey</a> adjustments (an adjustment which allows fo=
r a maximum number of strokes per hole based on the player's course handica=
p) have been applied, using the following formula:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
